'''Carlette D. Guidry''' (also known as '''Guidry-White''' and '''Guidry-Falkquay'''; born September 4, 1968 in [[Houston, Texas]]) is an [[United States|American]] former [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] who won the Olympic gold medal of the 4 x 100 metres relay in [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 in Barcelona]] and again in [[Athletics at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 in Atlanta]].<ref name="USATF">{{cite web |url=http://www.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2000/guidry.html |title=2000 USATF ATHLETE BIOGRAPHY  Carlette Guidry |year=2000 |publisher=[[USATF]] |accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=sportsref>{{Cite Sports-Reference |title= Carlette Guidry-White |url= http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/gu/carlette-guidry-white-1.html |accessdate= November 21, 2011}}</ref> She also competed in the individual 200m race in 1992 and 1996.<ref name=sportsref /> Guidry-White won a silver medal in the 60 metres event at the [[1995 IAAF World Indoor Championships]], which was coincidentally held in [[Barcelona]].<ref name="USATF" /> The same year she finished fourth at the outdoor championships. At the collegiate level, Guidry competed for the [[Texas Longhorns]] of the [[University of Texas at Austin]] between 1987 and 1991. She collected a total of twelve NCAA titles, and was named Southwest Conference Athlete of the Decade in indoor track and outdoor track and field for the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1992_1073766/sports-notebook.html |title=Sports notebook |date=1992-08-13 |publisher=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.texassports.com/sports/tex-relays/spec-rel/032911aaa.html |title=Carlette Guidry Falkquay to be recognized at this year's Texas Relays |last=Graney |first=Ryan |date=March 29, 2011 |publisher=[[Texas Longhorns|Texassports.com]] |accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref> She was also honoured as Indoor Track And Field Most Outstanding Student-Athletes In Honor Of The 25th Anniversary Of NCAA Women's Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/PressArchive/2007/Awards%2Band%2BScholarships/NCAA%2BNames%2BCarlette%2BGuidry%2Band%2BTrecia%2BKaye%2BSmith%2BDivision%2BI%2BIndoor%2BTrack%2Band%2BField%2BMost%2BOutstanding%2BStudent-Athletes%2Bin.html |title=NCAA Names Carlette Guidry And Trecia Kaye Smith Division I Indoor Track And Field Most Outstanding Student-Athletes In Honor Of The 25th Anniversary Of Women's Championships |date=February 28, 2007 |publisher=News Release of the [[NCAA]] |accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref>

