'''LaTasha Jenkins''' (born December 19, 1977) is an American former [[track and field]] [[sprint (running)|sprinter]]. Having won international medals in the [[200 metres|200 m]], she won a [[silver medal]] at the [[2001 IAAF World Indoor Championships|2001 World Indoor Championships]] and a silver medal at the [[2001 World Championships in Athletics|2001 Outdoor Championships]]. Other career highlights include 2001 U.S. Indoor 200m champion; 1999 and 2001 US Outdoor runner-up, 200m; 1999 NCAA 200m champion; four-time NCAA All-American; member of world record-holding 4x200m relay team. She was born in [[Chicago]] and attended Oak Lawn Polaris High School.<ref name=USATF>[http://www.usatf.org/athletes/bios/TrackAndFieldArchive/2003/Jenkins_Latasha.asp Latasha Jenkins]. USATF. Retrieved on 2015-06-28.</ref>

After winning the 1999 NCAA 200m title and finishing second to Marion Jones at the U.S. Championships, Jenkins was poised to make her mark on the international scene, but a collapsed lung she suffered on the flight to the 1999 World University Games forced her to with withdraw from that meet as well as the World Championships. She recovered in 2000 and in 2001 had terrific results under new coach Norbert Elliott in Georgia, winning her first U.S. title indoors and winning silver at the 2001 World Indoor Championships. She went on to finish runner-up to Jones outdoors at 200m and was fourth at the World Outdoor Championships. She graduated from [[Ball State University]] with a degree in English and a minor in counseling psychology. She scored 25 points at the Mid-American meet in 1998, and her 1999 NCAA crown was the first ever national championship for Ball State women's track & field.<ref name=USATF/>

Jenkins holds a [[List of world records in athletics|world record]], as a member of the American [[4 × 200 metres relay|4 × 200 m relay]] team that ran 1:27.46 on April 29, 2000 in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], the other team members being [[LaTasha Colander-Richardson]], [[Nanceen Perry]] and [[Marion Jones]]. Note that 4 × 200 m is not a regular track event and not a part of the program for any major international championship.

According to the [[Chicago Tribune]] in August 25, 2006, Jenkins had her A sample fail in a drugs test taken in late July that year. The discovered substance was [[nandrolone]]. Latasha Jenkins appealed the alleged tests and was later exonerated of all charges. She is the only athlete in history to win an anti-[[Doping in sport|doping]] case against USADA. WADA agreed with the findings of the USADA verdict and dropped their appeal.

Latasha Jenkins was inducted in the Ball State University Sports Hall of Fame in February 2009.

