'''Carmelita Jeter''' (born November 24, 1979) is an [[United States|American]] [[sprint (running)|sprinter]], who specializes in the [[100 metres|100 meters]]. She was the 2011 [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|IAAF World Champion]] in the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics – Women's 100 metres|100&nbsp;m]], and a three-time Olympic medallist.

She won the 100 m [[Bronze medal|bronze]] at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics]] and a [[Gold medal|gold]] at the [[2007 IAAF World Athletics Final|World Athletics Final]]. She won a second [[2009 World Championships in Athletics|World Championship]] bronze. Her victory in the [[Shanghai Golden Grand Prix]] in 10.64&nbsp;seconds made her the second fastest woman ever in the 100&nbsp;m, behind [[Florence Griffith-Joyner]]'s long standing [[Women's 100 metres world record progression|world record]]. Currently she holds three of the top ten times ever run.<ref>http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout=o/age=n/season=0/sex=W/all=y/legal=A/disc=100/detail.html</ref>

==Early life==
Jeter attended [[Bishop Montgomery High School]].<ref>{{cite web | title =Former BMHS, CSDH standout Jeter edges Lee for U.S. women's 100 title | work =Daily Breeze | publisher =MNG | date =June 27, 2009 | url =http://www.dailybreeze.com/csdh/ci_12701861 | accessdate =2009-09-15 }}</ref> Initially, [[basketball]] was the preferred sport in her family, and her younger brother, [[Eugene Jeter|Eugene]], later joined the [[Sacramento Kings]]. Her basketball coach suggested that she try out track, and an 11.7&nbsp;second run confirmed her natural talent for sprinting.<ref name=Rise/> Jeter graduated from California State University, Dominguez Hills which is located in Carson, California, with her bachelor's degree in physical education. Jeter set the record for most [[NCAA]] medals by a [[California State University, Dominguez Hills]] track athlete and became the University's first U.S. Olympic Trials qualifier. A recurring [[hamstring]] problem kept her out of competition for much of 2003–05, and it was not until 2007 that she made her first impact in senior [[track and field athletics]], having undergone treatment with [[deep tissue massage]].<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/athletes/bios/Jeter_Carmelita.asp Carmelita Jeter Biography]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref>

==International success==
[[File:Carmelita Jeter Osaka07.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Jeter at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 World Championships]]]]
In 2007, Jeter won a [[silver medal]] in the [[60 metres|60 meters]] at the [[USA Indoor Track and Field Championships]] with a personal best of 7.17&nbsp;seconds,<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/events/2007/USAIndoorTFChampionships/results/F20.asp 2007 US Indoor Championships Women 60 Meter Dash]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref> and she remained in good form, improving her 100&nbsp;m best to 11.04&nbsp;seconds to take fourth place in the 100&nbsp;m at the [[Adidas Track Classic]].<ref name=Rise>Arcoleo, Laura (2009-09-13). [http://www.iaaf.org/WAF09/news/kind=103/newsid=54389.html Jeter's rise continues, all the way to 10.67! – IAAF / VTB Bank World Athletics Final]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref> Building upon this, she qualified for her first major competition by finishing third at the national championships behind [[Torri Edwards]] and [[Lauryn Williams]].<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/events/2007/USAOutdoorTFChampionships/results/F40.asp 2007 US Championships Women 100 Meter Dash]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref> She went on to win the bronze medal at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]] in a personal best time of 11.02 seconds, as well as taking the 100&nbsp;m gold at the [[2007 World Athletics Final]].

The following year, she competed at the 100 and [[200 metres|200&nbsp;m]] [[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|U.S. Olympic trials]]. Although she set a 100&nbsp;m best of 10.97&nbsp;seconds in the quarter-finals,<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/events/2008/OlympicTrials-TF/results/Q2.asp Women 100 Meter Dash quarterfinals results]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref> she did not progress beyond the semifinals, finishing just two hundredths out of the qualifying positions.<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/events/2008/OlympicTrials-TF/results/S2.asp Women 100 Meter Dash semifinals results]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref> A sixth-place finish in the 200&nbsp;m meant she had not made the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] team, despite being one of the favourites for selection.<ref>[http://www.usatf.org/events/2008/OlympicTrials-TF/results/F4.asp Women 200 Meter Dash final results]. [[USATF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref> She qualified for the 100 and 200&nbsp;m races at the [[2008 World Athletics Final]], but only managed fourth and fifth place, respectively. She changed coach in November, deciding to work with [[John Smith (athlete)|John Smith]], who had previously coached athletes such as [[Maurice Greene (athlete)|Maurice Greene]]. Smith began completely remodelling Jeter's running style.<ref name=Rise/>

In her 2009 season, she showed strong performances going into the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics]]. She ran 7.11&nbsp;seconds in the 60&nbsp;m in the indoor season, the fastest by any athlete that year and a personal best.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout=i/age=n/season=2009/sex=W/all=n/legal=A/disc=60/detail.html 60 Metres 2009]. [[IAAF]] (2009-03-22). Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref> She remained in-form in her outdoor season, recording a fast 10.96&nbsp;seconds at the [[Mt. SAC Relays]],<ref>Lee, Kirby (2009-04-19). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=50249.html World leads for Jeter and Johnson in Mt. SAC Relays – Day 3]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-25.</ref> winning gold at the 2009 Nike [[Prefontaine Classic]], and taking her first national title at the 2009 U.S. Outdoor Championships.<ref>Morse, Parker (2009-06-27). [http://www.iaaf.org/WCH09/news/kind=100/newsid=51340.html Jeter and Rodgers take 100m titles in Eugene – US Champs, Day 2]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-06-30.</ref> At the 2009 [[London Grand Prix]], she placed first in the 100&nbsp;m, clocking a personal best of 10.92; it was the third fastest time at that point of the season, only slower than Jamaica's [[Shelly-Ann Fraser]] and [[Kerron Stewart]]. A week prior to the start of the World Championships, Jeter was part of a United States [[4 × 100 metres relay|4 × 100 m relay]] team that ran the fastest women's sprint relay in twelve years. Lauryn Williams, [[Allyson Felix]], [[Muna Lee (athlete)|Muna Lee]] and Jeter finished with a time of 41.58&nbsp;seconds, bringing them to eighth on the all-time list.<ref>Wenig, Jörg (2009-08-08). [http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=52607.html US quartet blasts 41.58 in the 4x100 as Wlodarczyk improves to 77.20m in Cottbus]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-08-09.</ref>

[[File:20090816-WK2009-Carmelita Jeter.jpg|thumb|Jeter running in the World Championships in Berlin]]

At the [[2009 World Athletics Championships]], in [[Berlin]], Jeter was one of the favourites for the gold medal as a 10.83&nbsp;seconds personal best in the semis made her the fastest qualifier for the final. She ended up with her second World Championship bronze medal in the 100&nbsp;m, however, finishing a tenth of a second behind Fraser and Stewart. The races after the championships proved more successful: she beat strong opposition in the [[IAAF Golden League]] meets in [[Weltklasse|Zurich]] and [[Memorial Van Damme|Brussels]] with two sub-10.90 runs.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/gle09/results/eventcode=4181/sex=W/disccode=100/combcode=hash/roundcode=f/index.html#detW100 2009 Weltklasse Zurich 100 metres W]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref><ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/gle09/results/eventcode=4178/sex=W/disccode=100/combcode=hash/roundcode=f/index.html#detW100 2009 Memorial Van Damme 100 metres W]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref>

Jeter was also selected to run as part of the US relay team as the anchor runner. However, in their heat, during the change over between [[Alexandria Anderson]] and [[Muna Lee (athlete)|Muna Lee]], Lee horrifically injured her leg which caused elimination from the relay event. [[Jamaica]] eventually claimed the gold medals.

She entered the [[2009 IAAF World Athletics Final]] having won her last three races by a significant margin. Even taking this into account, Jeter surprised with one of the highlights of the final edition of the [[IAAF World Athletics Final]].<ref name=Rise/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8253539.stm Stunning Jeter run upstages Bolt]. [[BBC Sport]] (2009-09-13). Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref> She won the 100&nbsp;m race in [[Thessaloniki]], [[Greece]] with a time of 10.67, to become the third fastest woman in history and set a championship record.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/WAF09/news/kind=100/newsid=54383.html Jeter – 10.67 – third fastest of all-time! IAAF / VTB Bank World Athletics Final]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-17.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jeter becomes 3rd fastest woman ever in 100|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2009-09-13-3893165225_x.htm|publisher=[[USA TODAY]]|author=Demetris Nellas|date=September 13, 2009|accessdate=September 14, 2009}}</ref> This was the fastest run in twelve years; a time which had only been bettered by [[Marion Jones]] and [[Florence Griffith-Joyner]],<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout=o/age=n/season=0/sex=W/all=y/legal=A/disc=100/detail.html 100 Metres All Time]. [[IAAF]] (2009-09-15). Retrieved on 2009-09-17.</ref> and 0.16&nbsp;seconds faster than Jeter had ever run before.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout=o/age=n/season=2009/sex=W/all=n/legal=A/disc=100/detail.html 100 Metres 2009]. [[IAAF]] (2009-09-16). Retrieved on 2009-09-17</ref> She ran even faster a week later at the [[Shanghai Golden Grand Prix]], winning in 10.64&nbsp;seconds (the fourth fastest time ever) to become the second fastest woman outright.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8265568.stm Gay clocks stunning 100m in China]. [[BBC Sport]] (2009-09-20). Retrieved on 2009-09-21.</ref>

Her fast times were a double-edged sword in that they brought as much suspicion as they did appreciation. At age 30, Jeter had improved her personal record by over a third of a second within a single season and she ranked between Jones and Griffith-Joyner in the all-time lists. Given the history of the women's sprints and speculation about [[performance-enhancing drug]] use, Jeter said "I can't be upset about those questions [but] It's unfortunate that I work this hard and I don't get the credit I should get".<ref>Kessel, Anna (2010-02-20). [http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/feb/20/carmelita-jeter-sprinter-too-fast Carmelita Jeter bears the burden of being the fastest woman alive]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on 2010-02-20.</ref> She improved her 60&nbsp;m best to 7.02&nbsp;seconds to win at the [[USA Indoor Track and Field Championships]]. This was still slower than [[LaVerne Jones-Ferrette]], and Jeter resolved to improve further for the [[2010 IAAF World Indoor Championships]].<ref>Lee, Kirby (2010-03-01). [http://www.iaaf.org/WIC10/news/kind=100/newsid=55711.html World Leads by Dunn, Trammell and Williams, Jeter jets 7.02 – USA Indoor Champs Day 2]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2010-03-01.</ref>

